    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="104"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d104">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72111/634a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to President
                            <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-12">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 12, 1914</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I enclose an opinion in regard
                    to the sale of Submarines.<note n="3" xml:id="d104fn1">No copy of this enclosure
                        found in Department files.</note> I fear that we would be “skating on thin
                    ice” if we adopted the rule suggested.</p>
                <p>It may be within the rules of neutrality but I am afraid we could not convince
                    the average citizen there was any difference in allowing a vessel to be
                    completed here and allowing the parts to be made so that a complete vessel could
                    be shipped and the parts assembled in another port.<note n="4" xml:id="d104fn2"
                        >For correspondence previously printed concerning the sale of submarines in
                        parts, see <ref target="frus1914Supp#pg_577">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1914, supp., p. 577</ref>;
                            <ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_782">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, 1915, supp., pp. 782</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1915Supp#pg_783">783</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>If you are in doubt about the matter I would like to talk with you before the
                    matter is finally settled, as I think there is danger in this proposition.</p>
                <p>With assurances [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
